There appear good grounds for believing that one, and perhaps the chief, of these was the now lost history of Livy. More than one incident, of which Lucan is now the earliest witness, is said to have been recorded in Livy, e.g. that of the Augur Cornelius 1. A predecessor of Lucan, Valerius Maximus, the ’ industrious collector of anecdotes, used Livy and refers to him 3 and there are some striking agreements between Lucan and Valerius Maximus-². A succeeding historian, L. Annaeus Florus, drew chiefly from Livy-‘³3 and Lucan and Florus are often in the closest agreement4. Lucan again must have been· naturally drawn to a writer whose treatment of the aristocrats was so ‘Pompeian⁶.' Nor is it superfluous to observe that the frequency with which Livy may be used for the illustration of Lucan’s phraseology points of itself to the same conclusion⁶.

So far as 1 know, no evidence is forthcoming that Lucan did actually draw from any other source. There is nothing to show that he used the lost history of Asinius Polli0‚ and if within the present book he made any use of the narrative of Caesar, it was certainly only for the purpose of contradicting it.
